e he was, he couldn't follow instructions &quot;properly&quot; – and on top of everything he really was the shortest kid in the class. When he got into first grade the teacher was surprised he didn't know how to write – &quot;kindergarten is the new first grade, other kids are much smarter than him&quot;.. His school years were disastrous (although he's a very bright child with a high IQ)..he's in a special high school now, where the student/teacher ratio is 8 to 1..he's doing fantastic academically, but is having lots of difficulties emotionally, he suffers from anxiety and he's a highly sensitive child. After all he was bullied for years by kids and teachers alike – he simply was not ready for anything other then play at such a young age. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1028" language="en" documentId="5284" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Marti58" date="November 13, 2012 at 8:46 am" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://schoolsofthought.blogs.cnn.com/2012/11/12/my-view-kindergarten-redshirting-different-for-each-child/comment-page-1" topic="redshirting" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="5284" notes="" title="My View: Kindergarten redshirting different for each child"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1028"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>